Import JHU CSSE Data

JHUs CSSE maintains a data repository https://github.com/CSSEGISandData/COVID-19 tracking all COVID cases of the most recent outbreak. Data is broken down into Confirmed, Deaths, and Recovered cases and updated daily.

We import the most recent data as follows:

(confirmed_raw = read_csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/CSSEGISandData/COVID-19/master/csse_covid_19_data/csse_covid_19_time_series/time_series_19-covid-Confirmed.csv"))

Data Cleaning

The data is imported as longitudinal/time-series data. I will use Dr.Zhous framework to convert the imported CSVs into long format:

confirmed = confirmed_raw %>%
  pivot_longer(-(`Province/State`:Long), 
               names_to = "date", 
               values_to = "confirmed") %>%
  mutate(date = mdy(date)) # convert string to date-time

Plot cumulative Confirmed cases

covid %>% filter(`Country/Region` %in% c("Mainland China", 
                                         "Macau", 
                                         "Hong Kong", 
                                         "Taiwan")) %>% 
  mutate(isHubei = ifelse(`Province/State` == "Hubei", "Hubei", "Others")) %>%
  ggplot() + 
  geom_col(aes(date, confirmed, fill = isHubei)) +
  labs(fill = "Province") +
  xlab("Date") +
  ylab("Cases") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("orange", "blue"))

Mapping China provinces using nCov2019

nCov2019 comes with a mapping module included (but only works with the up-to-date data).

current = get_nCov2019(lang = "en")
require(chinamap)
## Loading required package: chinamap
cn = get_map_china()
## Loading required package: sp
## Regions defined for each Polygons
cn$province = trans_province(cn$province)

plot(current, region = 'china', chinamap = cn, font.size = 2)

Use Dr.Zhous function to convert Chinese province names to English

translate <- function(x) {
  sapply(x, function(chn_name) {
    if (str_detect(chn_name, "")) {
      eng_name <- "Macau"
    } else if (str_detect(chn_name, "")) {
      eng_name <- "Taiwan"
    } else if (str_detect(chn_name, "")) {
      eng_name <- "Shanghai"
    } else if (str_detect(chn_name, "")) {
      eng_name <- "Yunnan"
    } else if (str_detect(chn_name, "")) {
      eng_name <- "Inner Mongolia"
    } else if (str_detect(chn_name, "")) {
      eng_name <- "Beijing"
    } else if (str_detect(chn_name, "")) {
      eng_name <- "Taiwan"
    } else if (str_detect(chn_name, "")) {
      eng_name <- "Jilin"
    } else if (str_detect(chn_name, "")) {
      eng_name <- "Sichuan"

Plotting 2019-nCoV incidence

Plot confirmed cases on a specific date

plotdate = "2020-01-31"

count <- "confirmed"

covid %>%
  filter(`Country/Region` %in% c("Mainland China", "Macau", "Hong Kong", "Taiwan")) %>%
  filter(date == plotdate) %>%
  group_by(`Province/State`) %>%
  top_n(1, date) %>% # take the latest count on that date
  right_join(chn_prov, by = c("Province/State" = "NAME_ENG")) %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_sf(mapping = aes(fill = !!sym(count), geometry = geometry)) +
  scale_fill_gradient(name = "Cases", 
                      trans = "log10", 
                      breaks = c(5, 50, 500, 5000, 50000, 100000),
                      labels = c(5, 50, 500, 5000, 50000, 100000),
                      guide = "legend",
                      low = "lightblue",
                      high = "red") +
  theme_bw() +
  labs(title = str_c(count, " cases"), subtitle = plotdate)
